Tax refund suit was brought by corporation, its sole shareholder, and the son of its sole shareholder arising from tax treatment of option to purchase one-half interest in parcel of real estate which was given by corporation to son for nominal consideration. The United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia, Charles A. Moye, Jr., J., ruled that grant of option resulted in constructive dividend from corporation to sole shareholder, measured by ascertainable value of option, and appeals were taken. The Court of Appeals, Goldberg, Circuit Judge, held that: (1) evidence supported district court\rquote s conclusion that income from sale of son\rquote s one-half interest in real estate to third party should not be imputed to corporation; (2) evidence supported district court\rquote s conclusion that sole stockholder received a constructive dividend from corporation by corporation\rquote s grant of option to son, but (3) court failed to apply proper standard for determining value of son\rquote s option at time of exercise and therefore improperly computed amount of sole stockholder\rquote s constructive dividend.
